ta Müller -- tThe Power of Language and Silence: Reinhard Jirgl’s Die Stille -- tWords and Music -- t“Disrupted Language, Disrupted Culture”: Hanns Eisler’s Hollywooder Liederbuch (1942-43) -- t“and all of a sudden, in the middle of it, they began singing . . .”: Languages and Commemoration in Arnold Schoenberg’s Cantata A Survivor from Warsaw (Op. 46) -- tTranslation -- tUnderstanding a Perpetrator in Translation: Presenting Rudolf Höß, Commandant of Auschwitz, to Readers of English -- tTranslating Testimony: Jakob Littner’s Typescript and the Versions of Wolfgang Koeppen and Kurt Nathan Grübler0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aNew perspectives on the relationship - or the perceived relationship - between the German language and the causes, nature, and legacy of National Socialism and the Shoah.There is seemingly no escaping the association of the language of Goethe with the language of Hitler: the two leaden clichés seem to be inseparable, suggesting a Sonderweg between enlightened sophistication and subtle beauty on the one hand and linguistic barbarism on the other. Victor Klemperer suggested that the Lingua Tertii Imperii was a perversion of German that needed to be purged from the language, but does the notion of "Nazi language" as an identifiably separate entity really hold water, or does it only reflect a desire to construct a clear demarcation line between "Germans" and "Nazis"? What new linguistic, literary, or historical perspectives are availableon the functioning of language during and after the Third Reich? Must German always be the "language of the perpetrators," entailing a constant state of heightened self-awareness or vigilance against contamination, or is neutral,objective speech about National Socialism possible in German? This collection provides new perspectives on the relationship - or the perceived relationship - between the German language in all its manifestations and the causes, nature, and legacy of National Socialism and the Shoah. Contributors: Ian Biddle and Beate Müller, Mary Cosgrove, Peter Davies, Sylvia Degen, Andrea Hammel, Geraldine Horan, Teresa Ludden, Dora Osborne, Marko Pajevic, James Parsons, Simone Schroth, Arvi Sepp, Simon Ward, Jenny Watson. Peter Davies is Professor of Modern German Studies at the University of Edinburgh. Andrea Hammel is Senior Lecturer in German at Aberystwyth University.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 0aAustrian literaturexHistory and criticism. 0aGerman literaturexHistory and criticism. 0aHolocaust, Jewish (1939-1945)zGermany. 0aHolocaust, Jewish (1939-1945), in literature. 0aNational socialism in literature. 0aNational socialism. 0aSwiss literature (German)xHistory and criticism. 4aEnglish & American Literature. 4aGerman Literature. 4aModern History. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Genocide & War Crimes.2bisacsh  aGerman Language.  aHistory.  aLinguistic.  aLiterary.  aNational Socialism.  aNazi Language.  aPerspectives.  aShoah.1 aBiddle, Ian, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCosgrove, Mary, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDavies, Peter, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDavies, Peter, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aDegen, Sylvia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHammel, Andrea, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHammel, Andrea, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aHoran, Geraldine, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLudden, Teresa, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMüller, Beate, econtributor.4ctb4https://i